nodes.html: As new candidates continue to enter the fray for the 2022 statewide races, two familiar names raked in the most cash out of the bunch: Maura Healey and Andrea Campbell.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 20.11

nodes.html: Healey, the state’s attorney general who’s launching a bid for the open governor’s seat, raked in $412,499 in the short month last month, her campaign confirmed, for a total of $4,237,371 in cash on hand.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 20.11

nodes.html: Healey’s Democratic rival, state Sen. Sonia Chang-Diaz, earned $106,607 in February, and with $351,058 in her bank. The two will face off in the Democratic primary this September.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 20.11
Element has sufficient color contrast of 20.11

nodes.html: Former challengers including Harvard professor Danielle Allen and former state Sen. Ben Downing have dropped out of the race. Both Chang-Diaz and Allen had branded themselves as progressives, potentially giving Chang-Diaz a financial boost now that Allen has exited the race.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 20.11

nodes.html: On the Republican side, former state Rep. Geoff Diehl’s campaign said it had not compiled its campaign totals yet. Diehl’s Republican challenger, businessman Chris Doughty, raised $34,000 in February, according to his campaign, and is in the process of hiring a fundraiser.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 20.11

nodes.html: In the attorney general race, former Hub mayoral candidate, city councilor and attorney Andrea Campbell raked in $329,488 in the first month of her attorney general campaign.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 20.11

nodes.html: Her challenger, 2018 Democratic lieutenant governor nominee Quentin Palfrey, ended February with $101,942 raised and $246,877 in cash on hand, and 160 endorsements.

any.message: Element has sufficient color contrast of 20.11

nodes.html: Labor attorney Shannon Liss-Riordan, who’s also vying for the seat soon vacated by Maura Healey, did not respond to the Herald’s request for her campaign numbers.

nodes.html: As new candidates continue to enter the fray for the 2022 statewide races, two familiar names raked in the most cash out of the bunch: Maura Healey and Andrea Campbell.

none.message: Element does not duplicate existing text in alt text

nodes.html: Healey, the state’s attorney general who’s launching a bid for the open governor’s seat, raked in $412,499 in the short month last month, her campaign confirmed, for a total of $4,237,371 in cash on hand.

none.message: Element does not duplicate existing text in alt text

nodes.html: Healey’s Democratic rival, state Sen. Sonia Chang-Diaz, earned $106,607 in February, and with $351,058 in her bank. The two will face off in the Democratic primary this September.

none.message: Element does not duplicate existing text in alt text
Element does not duplicate existing text in alt text

nodes.html: Former challengers including Harvard professor Danielle Allen and former state Sen. Ben Downing have dropped out of the race. Both Chang-Diaz and Allen had branded themselves as progressives, potentially giving Chang-Diaz a financial boost now that Allen has exited the race.

none.message: Element does not duplicate existing text in alt text

nodes.html: On the Republican side, former state Rep. Geoff Diehl’s campaign said it had not compiled its campaign totals yet. Diehl’s Republican challenger, businessman Chris Doughty, raised $34,000 in February, according to his campaign, and is in the process of hiring a fundraiser.

none.message: Element does not duplicate existing text in alt text

nodes.html: In the attorney general race, former Hub mayoral candidate, city councilor and attorney Andrea Campbell raked in $329,488 in the first month of her attorney general campaign.

none.message: Element does not duplicate existing text in alt text

nodes.html: Her challenger, 2018 Democratic lieutenant governor nominee Quentin Palfrey, ended February with $101,942 raised and $246,877 in cash on hand, and 160 endorsements.

none.message: Element does not duplicate existing text in alt text

nodes.html: Labor attorney Shannon Liss-Riordan, who’s also vying for the seat soon vacated by Maura Healey, did not respond to the Herald’s request for her campaign numbers.
